Q. What is Dependency Injection ?

Dependency Injection is a design pattern where the dependencies (objects a class needs) are
provided by an external source (the Spring container), rather than the class creating them
itself. This leads to loose coupling and easier testing.
It is the practical implementation of Inversion of Control Principle (IoC) , which ia a theory
or theology .


Types of Dependency Injection in Spring:

a. Constructor-based Dependency Injection:

How it works: Dependencies are provided through a class constructor.

Advantages:
Promotes immutability (fields can be final)
Ensures all required dependencies are provided at object creation
Easier to test (dependencies must be provided).

Implementation:

@Component
public class UserService {
    private final UserRepository userRepository;

    @Autowired
    public UserService(UserRepository userRepository) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository;
    }
}
With Spring Boot, @Autowired is optional on constructors if the class has only one constructor.

b. Setter-based Dependency Injection:
How it works: Dependencies are provided through setter methods after the object is constructed.

Advantages:
Useful for optional dependencies
Allows changing dependencies after object creation (not recommended for required dependencies)

Implementation:

@Component
public class UserService {
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    @Autowired
    public void setUserRepository(UserRepository userRepository) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository;
    }
}

c. Field-based Dependency Injection (Not recommended for most cases):

How it works: Dependencies are injected directly into fields.

Implementation:

@Component
public class UserService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;
}

Note: This approach is less testable and not recommended for production code.

Feature	                    Constructor Injection	            Setter Injection

Immutability	            Promotes (fields can be final)	    Not promoted (fields are mutable)
Required/Optional	        Good for required dependencies	    Good for optional dependencies
Testability	                Easy to test	                    Easy to test
Spring Usage	            Preferred for most cases	        Use for optional or circular deps